---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import CoupledWaveguides from '../../components/diagrams/CoupledWaveguides.astro';
import CoPropagatingModes from '../../components/diagrams/CoPropagatingModes.astro';
import CounterPropagating from '../../components/diagrams/CounterPropagating.astro';
import BlochSphere from '../../components/diagrams/BlochSphere.astro';

import QuantumTunneling from '../../components/diagrams/QuantumTunneling.astro';
import QuantumMeasurement from '../../components/diagrams/QuantumMeasurement.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Foundations of Quantum Mechanics">
  <section class="page-header">
    <h1>Foundations of Quantum Mechanics</h1>
    <p class="page-intro">
      Coupled mode theory (CMT) and quantum two-level systems share identical mathematical
      structure. A forward wave coupling to a backward wave in a waveguide obeys the same
      equations as a quantum particle tunneling through a barrier. Explore the connections
      through these interactive visualizations.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="diagram-grid">
    <div class="diagram-intro">
      <h2>Co-Propagating Coupled Modes</h2>
      <p>
        When two waveguides are brought close together, their evanescent fields overlap
        and energy transfers periodically between them. The coupling coefficient &kappa;
        and detuning &Delta;&beta; control the transfer efficiency and beat length.
      </p>
    </div>
    <CoPropagatingModes />
    <CoupledWaveguides />

    <div class="diagram-intro">
      <h2>Counter-Propagating Waves</h2>
      <p>
        In structures like Bragg gratings, a forward-traveling wave couples to a
        backward-traveling wave through periodic evanescent interaction. At resonance,
        the structure acts as a near-perfect mirror.
      </p>
    </div>
    <CounterPropagating />

    <div class="diagram-intro">
      <h2>Quantum Tunneling &harr; Evanescent Coupling</h2>
      <p>
        A quantum particle tunneling through a classically forbidden potential barrier
        is the same physics as evanescent coupling bridging the gap between waveguides.
        Both involve exponentially decaying fields in the forbidden region.
      </p>
    </div>
    <QuantumTunneling />

    <div class="diagram-intro">
      <h2>Bloch Sphere</h2>
      <p>
        The state of any two-level system — whether a qubit, a coupled waveguide pair,
        or a spin-½ particle — maps to a point on the Bloch sphere. Coupling rotates
        around the x-axis; detuning rotates around z.
      </p>
    </div>
    <BlochSphere />

    <div class="diagram-intro">
      <h2>Quantum Measurement as Coupled Modes</h2>
      <p>
        In the coupled mode theory of measurement, a system waveguide carrying |&psi;⟩
        is coupled to an initially empty measurement waveguide through an interaction
        operator A. As the modes co-propagate through the interaction region, amplitude
        builds up in the measurement channel. The coupling strength &kappa; and interaction
        length L determine whether this is a weak measurement (minimal back-action) or
        a strong projective measurement (significant state transfer).
      </p>
    </div>
    <QuantumMeasurement />
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .page-header {
    padding: 3rem 0 1rem;
  }

  .page-header h1 {
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .page-intro {
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    max-width: 720px;
  }

  .diagram-grid {
    padding: 1rem 0 2rem;
  }

  .diagram-intro {
    margin-top: 3rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .diagram-intro h2 {
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .diagram-intro p {
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
    max-width: 680px;
  }

  .static-figure {
    margin: 1.25rem 0;
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .static-figure img {
    width: 100%;
    display: block;
  }
</style>
